,Not Recommended,258970,30083706,Posted: 21 February,all,JunglePredator,"I cannot recommend ""Gauntlet"" as it is in its current form.Having pre-ordered the game I played it during the 1st week of release. At that point I was pleased with what I saw: the game was pretty & there was an upgrade system allowing one to quest for something. More like an RPG then an endless dungeon hack & slash. It was still Gauntlet of old but it wasinterestingnot the mindlessness of old technology.Because of some problems with the multiplayer with my friend it was set aside until tonight when, having an immense headache, I wanted something more light hearted to play then my other games at the moment, namely Dark Souls 3.And I've come to find a mess of a game. Gone is the beautifully rendered hub room replaced with a fairly ugly 2D map representing the dungeon. Also removed is any kind of upgrade or bonus system. So not having the hub room makes sense in a way... there's no reason to replay levels. However instead of selecting your current level on a map they should have just made you go to the next level automatically.The only thing left to purchase in terms of ""upgrades"" are talismans & relics. Or read properly: ""healing"" potions & magic potions.  The healing potions no longer heal you, the activate a skill that can earn health depending on the character you're playing. The relics replace magic potions... instead they recharge on a timer & are infinitely usable.Once you have the talisman & relic that suits your play manner there's no point for grinding as all that's left after you have your favorite is looks. New armour, new head or a cape if you try their new play type. All cosmetic & rather pointless since you can't really see that much detail in game anyways since it still plays from an overhead zoomed out dungeon style.Enemy redesign is not necessarily faithful to the original & in some cases is not intuitive. A prime example is the new ghost. Looking kind of ugly it looks like a sheet on a wire. However my 1st encounter with it it wasn't clear it was a standard enemy; it looked more like a spell effect. Flying through walls the ghost bared no resemblance to the original ghost; part of which was the ability to use the terrain to your advantage.Death however is similar to the original however unlike the original there does not seem to be a way to destroy it (or at least in the level it's introduced I could not find a way with my necromancer). Also it does not come when you're taking too long or pre-placed in certain areas, instead it's on a timer for the level (at least in the level it's introduced in).Overall the action is much slower than the original Gauntlet & I almost feel likeGet Medievalhas a more interesting playability.Considering all this I'm now regretting having pre-ordered the game & urge people to pass on another failed Warner Bros. project.Instead, if you're lucky enough to find it, I recommend the previously mentioned Get Medieval."
