,Recommended,258970,17987892,"Posted: 11 September, 2015",all,Janitorman,"To be completely honest, this was probably the most dissapointing game ive ever bought. Is it bad? No, just not that much fun. I get that the appeal of the gauntlet series lies in its multi-player performance rather than going through the game solo. It is true that the game is a lot more enjoyable with a buddy, or two, or even three. Additionally, i like what they did with the personality of the main characters; in that they either follow tropes (Thor and Wizard) or break them entirely (like Thief and Valkyrie). They're easily the best interpretations of the original 4 classes in gauntlet because this aspect has rarely been focused on in previous entries.As for the gameplay itself.... It's pretty repetitive. If you enjoy taking on hoardes of enemies using a small yet well animated number of combo's then you might enjoy this. However, what you may not enjoy is the length of the game. The main story line is short, As in there were three main bosses since last I played this. The first is a pretty well done first boss, the second is an intense boss fight, while the third is.... pretty dissapointing as the game was building up to something a lot more intense.Now I'll give credit where its due, and that goes to the dev team. Like many early access games, Gauntlet's day one build was pretty messy, with the multiplayer being accessed via hub. Unlike most early access games, the Dev team has actually been responding to complaints, glitch reports, balancing etc; and has been suprisingly dedicated to this game despite that its already hit its sales peak. They're admirable for what they're doing so I greatly appreciate that aspect of the game.In conclusion this was a dissapointing game upon release, but it also makes me optimistic that this same team could make a much better sequel.7/10"
