,Not Recommended,258970,17884376,"Posted: 4 September, 2015",all,Shurikane,"NOTE: This review is for the Slayer Edition.+++ Polished, consistent experience+++ Great gameplay difference between the four characters--- Uninspired art direction--- Repetitive slog with little variance between the proposed challenges--- Short and forgettable campaign, coupled with an overly drawn-out Endless Mode--- Multiplayer gameplay friendly to griefingGauntlet attempts the impossible task of recapturing the allure of a long bygone era when coin-op arcades were king.  For the exercise, although it did produce a fairly solid foundation, fact remains that the project is doomed to failure: the classic Gauntlet game just cannot exist in today's world without profound changes.  In keeping its design philosophy close to the now thirty year-old original, Gauntlet by its own definition offers but little replay value.  A paper-thin story is laid on top of enough artifices to make it all seem like a modern game, but the facade quickly shatters away, and the game's true nature is revealed within minutes: room after room of same-y monsters and spawners, lost in a maze with little personality of its own.Gauntlet feels a lot like a proof of concept, more than a genuine full-fledged game, and though Slayer Edition vastly improved on the first version, there is still a lot of work to be done for this to consider itself in any fashion a modern game adapted to today's world.  Right now, for the price, there are much more engrossing games in the same genre out there, with a lot more content and replay value."
,Recommended,258970,13926094,"Posted: 10 January, 2015",all,Nux,"This game is good, but with a few improvements it could have been great.The biggest issue seems to be a terrible lack of content, the game can be completed in just a few hours if you really stretch it and take your time.  The problem is the lack of levels, there are 3 types of arenas each with 3 floors and a boss floor, this gives you just 9 levels and 3 boss fights.  This issue was sort of addressed in the last update adding a colosseum mode where you can battle waves of enemies for new rewards. They also added a new character which cost 5$ to unlock, now this seems like a slap in the face, that's 1/4 of the games price for an extra character.  For a game with such a small amount of cntent it should have been free but I could have justified paying 1-2$ for it but not 5$.Cons aside this game does provide a good time especially if you have friends to play it with.  This game is all about co-op, it even has couch co-op which was a huge plus for me.  Each character has unique abilities and masteries which makes playing as each character fun and different in some way.  The masteries for each character are what give this game it's replayability factor.  Completing the masteries make your character stronger which make earning the rewards from higher difficulties that much easier.If your expecting something like Gauntlet Legacy you will be disappointed, but if your looking for a classic arcade style Gauntlet to play with friends then this is the game for you.  I personally don't think that it's worth the 20$ price tag, so I would recommend waiting for a sale."
