76561197996678922,Recommended,258970,12242950,"Posted: 26 September, 2014",all,Pscion Piper (Julie),"This isn't Gauntlet.This is a modern version of SmashTV, pretending to be Gauntlet.This is perfectly fine, if you like SmashTV... which I do.The path you take through the game is fairly linear. As you go through the game, you will constantly find yourself in self-sealing mini-arena rooms that suddenly spawn monster generators, spamming you with low-level mobs from multiple sides that can be taken out in 1 or 2 hits, and throwing a few medium or high-powered threats in with the swarms of cannon-fodder attackers. The rooms will remain locked tight until all the mobs and generators are destroyed, and only then can you proceed. In between clearing the rooms, you'll pick up treasure, food, and potions which fuel your purchased relic power-ups. The rooms, in any of the three worlds, will all look and feel very similar to each other with little variations. The pattern of kiting around the enemies, using speed to lead them into manageable groupings, and then taking them out when you have the tactical advantage will remain constant throughout the whole game.Even the cheesy, smarmy dialog between your character and the dungeon controller is similar to SmashTV.And, its fun... its actually a LOT of fun...... but its not Gauntlet.Classic Gauntlet, at its core, has just one simple game mechanic: Control the pacing.From the second you pressed start, your life force was a timer. Enemies reduced your time. Death drained your time. Traps stole some time and stunned you in place for a few precious seconds. The mazes, shifting walls, and teleporters all disoriented and frustratingly led you down the wrong paths, eating up time. The destrucible walls forced you to spend time to get through them. Hidden objects in plain-looking walls made you trade time for their advantages. Doors that led to only treasure made you spend your time in looting. Being ""It"" drew the monsters to you, devouring time. Special potions and abilities either assisted or made things more difficult, costing you those few seconds to decide if they were worth the time. Food replenished just a little time.Every new dungeon level had all of the monster generators in place at the start, pumping out mobs every second, and you had to manipulate the swarms by shooting, hand-to-hand battling, sniping through corners, absorbing the damage, or evading past them if it was advantageous... all to get to the exit with as much time as possible left in your life-force, and then do it again, and again, and again until the game was over in a pile of bones and keys.... and this new game has absolutely NONE of that in it. There is no sense of urgency, and very little to push your pace faster than you care to go.Your life bar never drains on its own. You can take 2-5 hits before dying. Food will fill the life bar toward its maximum, but no further.You can kite and circle your foes for as long as you want, in fact its to your advantage to do so as killing multiple mobs in continual succession gives you a bonus to your Kill-Streak, which helps to build up points toward Skull-Tokens, your Continues.Exploring is somewhat pointless... there are no secret walls that aren't visibly marked with cracks and nearby convenient barrels for blasting them open.There is just the somewhat direct path through the dungeon levels with pre-scripted encounters in arena rooms, with just enough keys to make it through the level you are on, and no random encounters to speak of. Major swarms of enemies can't really wander out of their areas because the generators don't appear until you enter the room and trigger the encounter, so your ability to use choke-points and the dungeon layout is limited, at best.This game is GREAT and a LOT of fun at what it really is... SmashTV dressed up to look and feel like Gauntlet.... its just not Gauntlet.(Incidentally, Devs?... SmashTV dressed up to look like SmashTV with this game engine at its core? I'd TOTALLY buy that for a dollar!!)"
