,Not Recommended,258970,20585552,"Posted: 17 January, 2016",all,weretable and the undead chairs,"Gauntlet is not a terrible game to kill some time with, especially if you play with friends but if you choose to pick it up I suggest that you only get it on sale.  It has too many flaws for me to recommend it at full price.It strays a bit from the classic titles but is still a pretty simple arcade-style game and does not get too bogged down with overly complex additions.  There are some light gear grinds in the game, you have a few different weapons and other items which you can purchase with gold and some cosmetic cloaks you can unlock through arenas, but that is about it.  It is pretty easy to get gold in the game although it can be a bit monotonous to grind enough to buy everything.  There is a campaign mode with three difficulties but no real story to speak of, not that this type of game needs one.  There is also an endless floor mode which starts extremely easy but ramps up to be quite difficult in a hurry.Endless mode should be where the game shines, unfortunately the levels are terribly unbalanced and you can go through several floors in a row that are easy enough to be boring only to have a floor with a very small room so packed with enemies that it is nearly impossible to kite, making it extremely tedious to proceed.  Also the camera in this game is absolutely horrible so if you are playing with friends and you end up kiting in opposite directions it will attempt to keep  all of you on screen rather than focusing on your character.  This can lead to you being stuck at the very edge of your screen not able to see what is happening around you.  I would say the camera was responsible for more of my cooperative play deaths than anything else.The Death mob is present but works differently than in Gauntlet 2.  He takes up quite a bit of screen real estate and has a huge aura which can sometimes make it hard to see other enemies and projectiles.  If he touches you it is an instant kill, at least on the classes I have played.  This could actually be somewhat fun on long corridors when you are constantly running and killing  what you can as you go, but when you get locked into a room with a large number of mobs, spawners and bullet-sponge minibosses and also have death and his giant blob of color to deal with, it stops feeling challenging and just feels cheap.The old Gauntlet games threw ridiculous hordes at you but the gameplay was just more enjoyable than it is here.   If Death was not quite as obnoxious and the camera did not continually cause problems I would find it easier to recommend.  If you want an okay coop game that you can get ten or twenty hours out of, pick it up on sale but do not expect too much out of it.  If you want to scratch the Gauntlet itch, just go fire up one of the old arcade titles because this game misses that mark."
