,Recommended,258970,12326015,"Posted: 2 October, 2014",all,Cremè Caramel,"I've had a lot of fun with this game so far. The characters each have their own advantages and disadvantages to complement their unique play styles. The game also proved somewhat challenging to beat on unfair difficulty. My only complaints are that it's currently a bit too grindy, requiring you to get over 200,000 kills to complete all of the class's mastery pages. Additionally, the devs have yet to implement random level generation akin to the old arcade-style Gauntlet. Instead, there are only three sections of the game, each is broken into 4 chapters. Three chapters in every set of four contain 3 levels each, the fourth containing the boss fight. Each set of 3 levels is mostly the same: the first always a challenge level with keys, locked doors, and monster summoners, the second always an ""escape level"" of sorts with a constantly respawning threat (Death, spiders, demons), and the third an arena-style level with monster summoners that takes place in one room. Furthermore, all of the bossfights have the very simplified mechanic of avoiding the boss for a set amount of time until they become vulnerable, then attacking them for about 5 seconds before they become invincible again. Rinse and repeat. Despite these complaints, the game is still a lot of fun to play with friends provided two or more of you didn't want to play the same class. This game is worth it if you can spit the cost of the four pack, but I'd wait for it to go on sale to buy it just for yourself unless you already have people to play it with."
