76561197966676194,Recommended,258970,12227946,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,wr41thx,"TLDR: $20 gets you a fun coop experience with a few bugs that need to be hashed out.  Game is not that deep, but what were you expecting from a more faithful reboot of an arcade game from 1985?  Definitely worth it if you have friends.Let's just get this out first and foremost: This is a $20 reboot of a classic arcade game.  Have you played the original arcade game in a while?  It is about as vanilla of an experience as you can get.  It could easily be described as a fantasy themed, slower paced, robotron with keys in a maze.  Am I bashing the original game?  Hell no, it's a classic and a blast - but I wouldnt call it deep.  If you are looking for a complete reimagining of the series, then stick to Dark Legends or many of the other 4 player top down / isometric cooperative games that are more modern (Diablo, Sacred 3, etc)So what do we get for our $20?We get a much prettier 1985 Gauntlet with a few modern twists in the form of relics and perks.  Level flow is very methodical.  It's handcrafted dungeon (as per described in the trailer), procedurally generated level with some kind of theme (Death, Darkness, Lava bombs per world respectively), Arena Fight, then boss.  You can beat the game in about 3-5 hours on normal.  Honestly after beating it 2P with my wife, I have to agree that the real game shines on hard or insane with 4P.  This is where cooperation is key and little set backs (like the famed shooting the food) create that fun ""tension"" between the players.We get the original 4 classes, with some significant differences between them.  The Valkarie has a defensive shield, a spear dash, and a Captain America-esque sheild throw.  She is a defensive player that can trade her best defensive skill for her best offensive skill (shield throw disables block).  The Elf has rapid fire arrows, a high powered sniper shot, and bombs (that eventually become tied to the sniper shot).  This is your low hp hit and run character with burst damage.Then we get to the two most (appropriately in a thematic sense) opposite characters in the game - The wizard and the warrior.The warrior is rather bland with a medium cooldown AOE attack, two basic melee attacks, and a dash with a rather long charge time.  Some of his perks seek to spice him up slightly, but it feels like he is simply not quite as unique as the remaining characters.  He needs something to stand out, and it feels like the least amount of time was devoted to fleshing him out.  He has a powerful cleave that can one shot basic enemies - but it has a small area of effect thus rendering it really only useful towards attacking spawners.  Maybe he improves with perks, but he feels initially weak - which is not the impression to make with a hulking muscle bound killing machine with a 5 foot long broad axe.The wizard on the other hand is the utility character.  Many will note that the game is made by the same team who worked on Magicka, and his spell system is very similar to a watered down version of the one found in said game.  For those accustomed to DOTA2, he is very similar to Invoker.  He has low hp, but has the most versatile skill set of the entire game.  Merlin has various forms of AOE crowd control, a teleport, and decent damage output.  He has the potential to be the single most powerful character in the game once you are practiced with switching between his nine(!) available spells.This is entirely my opinion - but the Wizard is aboslutely brilliant and is by far the most entertaining character to play in the entire game.So, as has been noted by fellow reviewers, there are some balance issues in the game.  Some characters are simply more well rounded than others.   Some are exceedingly more complicated, but far more rewarding as well (Im looking at you Merlin).  It feels that the relic system, which allows characters to purchase special abilities that are useable via potions found in the dungeons, could have been used to balance this better - but everybody can purchase and use the same relics.  It may sound restrictive in a sense, but perhaps it would have been best to allow only certain characters to purchase certain relics.  Especially in the case of the very vanilla warrior and the overly versatile wizard.There are some definite bugs as well - Crypts (World 1) 1-2 has a reoccuring bug where doors will not open or keys will not spawn.  I've encountered this bug at least 3-4 times, and it forced us to restart the level to progress.  My wife and I have experienced crashing issues.  There are issues selecting resolutions in the graphical settings and the game doesnt play especially friendly with dual monitor configurations.  Some players are noting GPU overheating issues when vsync is disabled as well.Overall, however, I felt the need to write this review because I am sincerely enjoying the game.  It really shines with 4 players on hard or insane, but is a fun romp even on normal with 2 players.  I feel the price is perfectly acceptable for the amount of content this game provides, as well as the ability to play it online or couch coop.  If you approach the game with the expectations of what it really is - a more faithful remake of an arcade classic - then I am sure you will not be disappointed."
