,Recommended,258970,12220385,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,Zii'lyeh,"Pure dungeon crawling - you and up to 3 other players take on the Gauntlet, a giant magical labyrinth summoned by the powerful wizard Morak. You control your character (there are for - the heavy hitting warrior, the quick and defensive Valkyrie, the Wizard who deals in a large number of spells, and the Elf archer) from a bird's eye perspective, killing monsters and picking up loot. The eventual objective is to find 3 amulets and give them to Morak for power unimaginable.The graphics are reasonably good looking without interfering too much with the gameplay - a plethora of effects add a splash of colour to a game that is otherwise somewhat dull (greys n browns). You'll be too busy paying attention to the horde of mummies running after you to really pay that much attention. The view distance is also high enough that you don't really need to worry much about fine details. Music is a simple background melody encouraging you to keep on hacking and slashing - as for effects, monsters grunt, missiles bounce off the valkyrie's shield with a DINK and the wizard spells zap and boom entertainingly. Voice acting is rather lacklustre but is hardly an integral part of the game.From a control perspective, each character has their own set of light attacks, heavy attacks and special abilities - the wizard using a 2 button combo system to cast a wide variety of spells from 3 elements (storm, earth and fire). The response on both gamepad and Keyboard/Mouse is good, with minimal delays in the character doing what you want.The game does feel like it lacks a bit of variety - the problem with being a faithful remake is that after a little while things start to get a bit samey, but adding a friend or two to the mix can bring up the replay value immensely. There's even an element of competitiveness as the game tracks how much gold you obtain and how many kills you make, as well as a ""crown"" that can be taken off monsters each level to give a single player a significant bonus. Watching a group of people chase after a shiny hat while more and more mummies pop out of the ground is amusing, to say the least.Overall, Gauntlet takes a simple concept and does it well. It's definitely a good match for Diablo or Torchlight players, even though there is minimal progression aside from upgrading your relics and masteries (which provide minor bonuses) the game has few lulls and keeps your attention through constant, unrelenting action."
,Recommended,258970,12239575,"Posted: 25 September, 2014",all,Danimal66,Fantastic reenvisioning of a classic game I grew up with. Worth every penny at $20
76561198032919000,Recommended,258970,12264047,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,Kuryux,"The game feels like its not complete, as if they had to launch it earlier or, more likely, they took many features out in order to earn more later with downloadable content.The ""items"" are actually only outfits, not giving any bonuses. The relics are very few, only around 10. The levels feel nothing like the original, There is NOTHING randomized. Every time I repeat a dungeon, it feels like the same thing over and over again.The original had 5 worlds with tons of levels each that made you feel like you were in an epic adventure, finding your way in a huge labyrinth. In this version there are only 12 levels, and most of them are way too linear. Not to mention the bugs.... my character oftens becomes extremely slow, as if I was in slow motion, then I have to watch everyone else kill everything while I can barely walk.With all that said, its still nostalgic and yet innovative, considering the price, I would still recommend it for fans of the original."
