76561198011327106,Recommended,258970,12228138,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,Spirit,"Is this a great game? Yes.Is this a great Gauntlet game? Not really.I might be blinded by nostalgia (this is a nostalgia review) but, Gauntlet Legend on N64 forged in my mind what a Gauntlet game should be. Then, I got Gauntlet Dark Legacy on GameCube and the game kept everything I loved in the N64 version and added a crazy amount of content.Sadly, this game went away from a lot of element I loved about the past 3D Gauntlet. From what I played so far, it did bring some new interesting ideas, but sadly it got rid of a lot of what I consider the ""core"" of Gauntlet. In this state, it felt a bit more like a clone of Diablo 3.-- Improvement from previous Gauntlets --- Small puzzle to make the game feel a bit less repetitive. (Sadly they do reuse the same kind of puzzle a bit too often)- Actions like grabbing an explosive barrel. (Didn't like that the barrel could respawn)- Achievements to upgrade your hero.- Boss that require more thinking to kill effectively.- The potion use for the special ability is a great mechanic.- Unique way to play each type of hero.-- What is missing from previous Gauntlets --- Collectible! Where are my runes?- A lively overworld. (It does look really dull without theme levels)- Not a fan of the new way enemy portals works. (My biggest complaint)- No levelling up! (I did love the level grind when I was to weak for some boss)- No easy way to upgrade what your hero needs. (Strength / Speed / Armor / Magic)- Don't like how often you need to kill all enemies in a room to open gates.- Keys are too static and don't give the player much choices. (I miss these trap chest! haha)-- TLDR --Overall, if you like the dungeon crawling style in general, for the price, this is a great game.On the other hand, if you expect something like Gauntlet Legends or Gauntlet Dark Legacy, you might be disappointed."
