,Recommended,258970,12228258,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,Xanstus,"I am going to be honest.  The game itself is short.  Does not take too long to play through the entire game.  The upgrades don't do much but give you different looking stuff, not that there is anything wrong with cosmetic upgrades.  Relics are a nice touch and give players a life line when they are in serious trouble.  I would recommend playing the game on normal to start with as at higher difficulties enemis spawn quicker and become tougher which is hard to deal with when first starting out.  The actual character upgrades come from achievements completed throughout the game, death being part of those achievements.  I played through the game with a wizard and I would STRONGLY suggest to play with a controller and not a keyboard and mouse, it is very much designed with controllers in mind.  Wizard works in an interesting way where you press a combination of buttons to set a certain spell to attack with.  Each spell having a different range and bringing different benefits with it.  Each floor is setup in three stages: Exploration, escape/run for your life, and Survival (in that order).  It can become repetative and nothing really changes through different playthroughs.  All of this said, it is still an enjoyable experience.  The kind of joy that comes from taking hordes of monsters head on and coming out of it victorious.  It is still very much a Gauntlet game in its roots.  Fight large hordes, pillage all the loot, look for keys, and eat some of that sweet sweet food.  If afters reading this you have reservations about the price then I would wait a while until it goes on sale but I do suggest that at some point you give it a try because I believe it is worth your time."
