,Recommended,258970,12221808,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,mmm!5NATCH,"Since its debut in Arcades in 1985, The four player co-op hack and slash has returned to HD screens of today!Gauntlet has been considered to be one of the very first dungeon crawler games.So you can expect this game to maintain that style of play, swarms of medival monsters surrounding you and your friends while you either chop them up with an axe, fire arrows from a distance or use spectaclar magic to blast them away. but has Gauntlet changed since we last played it? or is still the same and just been given a HD recycle and reboot?The game can be enjoyed from Single player to Four.  local (couch co-op) with all players on screen on your pc or you can play online with some random players. If you and a friend want to play local and join online with others, you can.For people who havent bought this game and arent sure about the controllers. here's a brief low down.it'll be important to consider checking the steam forums first to see if your USB controller is supported. It would be reommended to play this game with a controller however if you don't have one, you can still you the keyboard and mouse. Using the keyboard and mouse will only count as 1 player.  so If you and a friend want to play together on the one screen someone will need a USB controller.with that out of the way, The four classes to choose from.Warrior, Valkyre, Wizard and Elf. With no introduction needed, The Warrior is your staple hack and slash champion. He will fearlessly surround himself with numbers of enemies and have them all decaptiated within seconds. While he has brutal power and strength, he does not have any ranged abilites and even when under attack by swarms enemies, he'll still need some cover from behind every now and then. He's trademark spell is a spin attack.Valkyre seems to be a mix of warrior and speed. She has a broadsword and sheild which helps her be a very balanced fighter in the game. She can hold her own in melee and has some limited range when she throws her shield much like Captain America of the Marvel Comics. Her most useful feature could be that ability or the fact that she is the only character in the game who can block off attacks and push back enemies.The Wizard could be the hardest class to use in the game but also be very useful to all parties. He is able to cast up to nine different spells but will need to hit 2 buttons in a pattern before performing them. He's fragile and needs to stay away from combat but the variety of magic spells, and the correct timing is critical when the team is overwelmed by minions. He wont be a favourite for many because of how he played, but he will definately well appericated by all.The Elf is a fully ranged unit and very fast. With an unlimited supply of arrows, He will fire endlessly in any direction you wish, He has dodge feature which will save you sometimes. Has a sniper shot which needs aimming that does a little more damage than the average arrow and can drop a bomb on unsuspected creatures should they get too close.Whatever your style of play is, one of these characters will be suited for it, However. It may be a little disapointing but there can only be one of each class for a team. So if you and a friend want to be the same class. It can't happen. Also, colours cannot change and names of the characters will stick too.The core gameplay of Gauntlet remains.Enter a dungeon, Monsters attack you, Sometimes theres a generator that keeps pumping them out. If you can take that out, they stop getting spawned. Along the way you collect loot, buy new gear, if you get hurt, Eat food. Get to the end of the level. Rinse, Repeat.It's downfall would be its taken away the many unlockable characters from previous games, items and bonus rooms all together and while potions are still available to use, they're not longer like the 'grenade style' games instead they act as fuel for your relics power.But ultimately, Its a very short game, and only Three dungeons, This comes as a shock to even the most veteran of players because this just isn't what Gauntlet would be remembered before, Because of this it would have to be the shortest Gauntlet game in the entire series and would only get its replay value from grinding on harder difficulties.However, Gauntlet replicates arcade action. Theres no time for any depth to the story (There is a story but I dont really care) but usually these kind of arcade games you dont need to worry about that. It's appeal will come from  getting in it there and being under pressure from numbers of enemies swaming to you in a corner and doing everything you can to stay alive. It would most likely appeal to that retro gamer who has strangely got some unique desire for being treated to unfair difficutly from the AI. and by the way here's a heads up. This is NOT an easy game and It may have you easily frustrated and annoyed but when you over come a large mob of critters. You get that lovely sense of relief and you feel pretty damn good.As you travel throught different areas you will be collecting money to spend at the shop. Unfortunately Im jotting this down as a negative part of the game. Collecting money is great, sure, but whats the point? The shop is limited and there is only two sections to shop with. Relics and clothing. At this point of time, I can say the clothing is cosmetic and has no benefit for your characters. And I feel that dressing them up in this gear is a tad pointless when you're mainly looking at your character from a birds eye view and far away anyway. Unless your clothing is used to show off to others you have achieved something, because while clothing is not only expensive for your character, It's also only available to you for purchase when you have beaten certain levels on a difficutly setting.The relics however are useful, and you can eqiupt two on a single character at the same time, These relics may be like a freezing smart bomb, turn a monster into food or even give you faster attack speed for a limited time. They can be upgraded as well a few times but thats it really. Apart from these options money doesnt serve any other purpose in the game. There's no extra items to carry or leveling up abilities. that's all changed over to the in game achievements.The more you play the better. Each of your classes will benefit from numerous dungeon crawls and even when you die!the ingame achievement system will let you unlock some slightly different perks which may assist you in later levels and possibly harder difficulties, but you wont be able to max things out to a ridiciolous number but you'll need to kill many many baddies if you want to reach these achievements!Backgrounds and enviroments are well detailed. You can have some fun destroying the props near by for a chance at loot and whenever you end a skirmish, You'll be left with fire marks on the ground, broken and barrles and even blood from enemies killed remain stained on the ground. While it helps the enviroment to look this way, It can be a little bit dull, but given the game's tone of dusty hallways, creepy caves and firey pits. It make sense for it to look this way.I recommend this game for the fact that its challenging and it's a bit more action orientated than some hack and slashers. It doesnt have the depth weapon system and spells as Diablo nor the RPG elements of putting certain points to stats. It's a get your weapon, dive in with a friend and slaughter all those that wanna kill you. The shop could go with some improvement but either way, The repeat value may come from grinding to get those acheivements so you can get those perks, or just enjoyment of pitting yourself in the hardest difficutly and seeing if you can actually survive (doubt it). Maybe you and a bunch of friends wanna do one of those classic all nighters and see how far you can get? whatever it may be. Gauntlet will definately still provide some good fun for all"
