76561198147074614,Recommended,258970,12237787,"Posted: 25 September, 2014",all,Bath,A lot of great fun.  I highly recommend the game.
76561198135285089,Recommended,258970,12252835,"Posted: 26 September, 2014",all,Rue,"[Reviewed on 9/26/14]Gauntlet - the remake of the original 1985 arcade game of the same name.  I imagine most people who grew up in the 80s knew of it quite well.  The age where arcades were still thriving business ventures and kids would come home from school and spend the afternoon sinking token after token into their favorite machines.  Gauntlet was one of those favorite machines for many.  So, the real question is ""How does this version stack up?""  Quite well, in my opinion.  The core gameplay is all there.  Despite being a largely cooperative venture, the game still allows for some of your favorite griefing tactics that were ever-so-present in the original.  You can shoot the food and steal other players' gold and you still have the four-player co-op in the form of the Elf, Wizard, Valkyrie, and the Warrior.  The controls are as simple as the original's were.  You've got your movement keys (or sticks, if you're using a gamepad), your basic and strong attacks, a special evasion/speed move, and a special attack.  The game feels fluid.  Everything from the combat and movement, to the seemless transition from room-to-room when you're crawling through the dungeons with your buddies.  The game does allow for solo play, if the player so wishes, but Gauntlet, at its core, is meant to be a cooperative experience.In that regard, I recommend you find friends to play with, as here comes the negative bit of the review.For one, there is no built-in communication function in this game.  At all.  No text chat; no voice chat - nothing.  This essentially means that if you and your teammates happen to be getting slaughtered over and over again, there is literally no way for you to attempt to coordinate a strategy.  You will be forced to befriend the individuals on your team, and start communicating through Steam's chat function if you are playing with randoms.  Playing with already established friends can help you sidestep this issue.  The game's difficulty does scale depending on the number of people you're playing with.  Which means that if you're playing with some particularly unskilled individuals, your experience may be arguably harder than simply playing by yourself.  This makes the inability to communicate your thoughts even more frustrating.  Additionally, for whatever reason, the game, which is not especially graphically demanding, seems to heat up my Radeon 7970 much higher than most games.  I'm not the only one to experience this, but turning on v-sync in the game itself and using Afterburner helped mitigate issues.  The only other complaint I have about the game is the fact that keymapping is currently an impossibility.  Sure, the game only has a few controls, but it's a PC-exclusive title and a standard feature amongst PC games was left completely absent (even after two patches at this point).  Regardless, the game is still a ton of fun.  It's addictive.  Hack & slash style gameplay with a stylistic art direction coupled with the ability to get a HUGE challenge from playing the game on its hardest difficulty is what is going to keep you coming back.  The game itself is relatively short.  It only has 12 levels.  Three stages, with four dungeons in each.  Each dungeon has three stages in itself, but it you can't start each dungeon from a checkpoint.  You always start it at the very beginning, unless you die.  In which case, you simply respawn at the beginning of the stage in which you died.There are bosses at the end of every one of the three sections.  At least two of them will provide you with a significant challenge.  Beyond that, you also have the ability to change your character's appearance with purely cosmetic items.  These items are purchased by a vendor in the hub area with the gold you acquire in the game itself.  Worry not, there are NO microtransactions in the game.  And, as I said, the items you purchase offer only cosmetic incentives.  The game also features a pseudo-leveling system.  In actuality, as you play the game and complete certain challenges - covering everything from destroying props and taking damage, to killing monsters and eating food - your character increases in ability.  He/she will get stronger and faster and luckier (in regards to finding gold) as you continue to play the game.  And then are the potions.  Potions are used to allow you to activate your abilities granted to you by items called 'relics' that you can buy from the vendor.  They offer you the chance to do things like freeze your enemies in place, heal yourself, or even turn your enemies into turkeys.  It's a good bit of fun, and they are certainly game-changers and life-savers on the harder difficulties.Altogether, Gauntlet is an awesome game.  It's just plain fun.  It's accessible, but it still offers a steep challenge to those looking for it.  If you like the original, I can't guarantee that you'll like this one, but I would be more than willing to imagine that you would.  For a $20 game that has dedicated developers already looking to improve the areas in which it's lacking (evidenced by two patches in a one-day span of time), and is a product that is already very well put together, I have to recommend the game to anyone who enjoyed the original, likes dungeons crawlers, or is just looking for a game that will give them simple enjoyment.  If I had to attach a numerical rating to the game, I would give it a solid 8/10."
76561197966843351,Recommended,258970,12253804,"Posted: 26 September, 2014",all,Dj Curley,"Fun game, and perfect for the casual gamer to get their fix. If you played the original, then this is a total winner. If you never did, it's a great game for the price."
76561197964866568,Recommended,258970,12264064,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,Crusader_bin,"Gauntlet returns in glory, bringing in a lot of co-op fun.You play as either Elf, Wizard, Warrior or Valkyria.Elf - a constant barrage of ranged damage, special skill is a bomb that does AoE damage.Warrior - Warrior flies on a magic carpet, with a sniper rifle and rocket launcher as a special skill.No. Warrior hacks and slashes. What did you expect? His special is even more hacking and slashing.Valkyria - Less offensive than warrior, seconadary attack is actually a shield block instead, special allows for a more flexible attack.Wizard - Has a lot of different spells, so it kind of feels like few classes cramed into one. Has supportive spells, variety of offensive spells from long range, medium or close. Is is the most difficult class, but overall can be most usefull as well.Game only offers 12 stages of varying length (3 of those are boss battles, that are rather short). You can play those on Easy, Medium, Hard and Very Hard modes. Those were balanced quite well. I mean, hard IS hard.The difficulty raises with more players present. Playing alone can quickly get boring, but playing with a team of 4 randoms usually turns into frantic running.For me it feels the best to play with 4 players that you know or 2 when joining/hosting randomly - that way it is easy to coordinate and share stuff between players, even without any form of communication inside the game.You can unlock a variety of items and upgrade them up to 3 levels. They give additional skills (up to 2 at a time) but those need potion pickups to be used. In 4 player team, that will be quite rare.The game can be finished in 3-4 hours, but it is meant to be replayed a lot.Overall, it can get boring over time, unless more areas (DLCs?) arrive.7.5/10 would be my score. Not saying the game is bad, it just feels small... In size, vision, length. Otherwise it delivers a lot of fun and I can recommend it. Old school to the bone :)"
