,Not Recommended,258970,12334540,"Posted: 2 October, 2014",all,Get a Cleu,"I purchased this game with the fond memories of Gauntlet Legacy, my all-time favorite arcade game that would suck away my quarters to no end. The game I got has the bare bones of the old Gauntlet Legacy game, there are indeed spawning structures that must be destroyed and and endless spawning of minions until they are destroyed... but something is lost in this reiteration of the game. There are a couple of things different that change the game drastically that I think one should know before purcashing this game.1. The levels are rather small and lacking in the same grandour that the levels in GL used to produce. In addition after playing for a couple of hours all the levels start to blend together until it's more like having 3 stages your run through repeatedly. Even though each stage has 3 areas they all follow a similar kind of routine. The areas you run through go in this order- you run around a smallish map,  you run through a narrow map that has similarish rooms, you fight in one big room an annoyingly large amount of monsters; honestly it gets boring after a while.2. Killing the spawning buildings. These buildings are massive tanks that can tank dozens of hits from any class. In GL the buildings weren't absolute tanks and the monsters weakened the futher the buildings were destroyed. This is NOT the case in this one, this leads to monsters becoming a huge annoyance. As I found myself playing wizard in unfair mode I found it a simple matter of flame jumping onto the building, using forceshield, icebeam in a rinse and repeat measure was a simple way of taking down buildings in the hardest difficulty!!! This means to me that the way they have buildings is just a way to inflate the amount of time spent trying to clear a level to make up for a lack of map size.3. The next thing I miss from GL is the boss fights. The boss fights in this current rendition of the game are long, tedious,  and relatively easy. The final boss is a little tricky but even then isn't that hard to a new player as long as they know how to control their characters by doing the basic tutorial where the game does an excellent job of explaining some of the more complex aspects.As I see it, this game is just the newest rendition of the games that use the title of Gauntlet, however I shalls till miss seeing the gold coins and pile of bones when I complete a level, of being able to go super size, or to tri-shot with archer. Honestly this game is okay with the little nuances they have added, but for it to truely be the Gauntlet I yearn for then""I REQUIRE MORE SUSTENANCE!"""
