,Not Recommended,258970,30579149,Posted: 17 March,all,rock3rd,"DISCLAIMER: I never played the original Gauntlet.This game, at its core, is extremely fun. I love the graphics, the sound, the art style, everything. Combat feels fluid and fast-paced, along with fun and (sometimes) useful abilities. All this should make a perfectly good game, right? Well, yeah. However, this game has one fatal flaw that makes playing it (at least in multiplayer) frusturating and slow.This game can be played with friends, as do most Arrowhead developed games. I LOVED Magicka 2, and I was expecting this to be a similar experience. In short, it's not, but this game does have many upsides. Despite this, singleplayer is pretty boring, with it being repetative and dull. It's not a terrible experience, but just not varied enough to make sufficient gameplay. Obviously, the main focus for this game was multiplayer, which is amazing- except for one thing. The progression in multiplayer for many players is downright insulting.In this game, there are a variety of items to buy, ranging from weapons, to vanity items, to abilities, or relics. These items are part of what make the game interesting: even in singleplayer. They are not gained through leveling up, but rather the game currency. Gold coins. Now, the thing about gold coins is that they are fundamentally broken and singlehandedly ruin the game's intended experience. They are not fair, especially to slower players or classes, such as the warrior. Also, players are barely rewarded for playing well to the point where it shouldn't even exist. We're talking getting 500 kills, getting 2,000 extra gold, and realizing you needed 14,000 more to get the CHEAPEST weapon (for the warrior at least).The problem with this and multiplayer is that it creates a competitive setting, where it is almost impossible to split all the gold 50-50. Each run has TONS of gold, all of which can be aquired in singleplayer and multiplayer. However, the need for gold creates a riff where you should be having fun, and instead, you end up avoiding enemies (which is the opposite of the game's goal) to get as much gold as possible. Instead of each new room being confronted with strategy, it's all just a race of ""Who can get the most gold in this room"". As a result, players actually playing the game and killing monsters are penalized, by not getting very much gold. Also, to add on top of that when you die, you drop a portion of your gold, which players can pick up. This makes it hard for players carrying the team to make any money as a result of dying so much. Finally, for the cherry on the cake, there are crowns in the game, which give bonuses cash at the end of each floor. However, instead of allowing players to keep their crown they EARNED, other players wait for the crowhnj-holder to die, by not helping them, taking all the food, etc..This a bad game design, and I would have to give this game a 3/10, ruined by it's inability to create a consistent progression system. The only way to have fun would be by unlocking all gear for every class, but that won't happen anytime soon.tl;dr: An otherwise great game ruined by it's flawed and competitve progression system, where players literally help their teammates die, in order to get enough gold to get good gear. Not the player's fault, but the game."
