76561198048249227,Not Recommended,258970,33384909,Posted: 8 July,all,fortuiteer,"EDIT:When I previously decided to write this review, my patience was worn a bit thin by repeated instantaneous kicks from public games. Back then I fleetingly started a singleplayer game to get a look at the hosting options but couldn't find them where I expected them. As it turns out, the host only gets to change any of the settings after choosing the game mode and difficulty, while already in the lobby.That seems a bit counterintuitive to me, since that means a stranger could be able to join the lobby before the host is able to reach the menu with the privacy settings, but at least they are available.Regardless of that I won't change my opinion. For a game of this type a server browser seems like the only reasonable choice. I don't want to repeatedly try my luck with a ""Quick Join"" button that brings me to a random and entirely anonymous server.Gameplay feels floaty and never seems rewarding. I wouldn't say this lightly since my perception of video games is usually not blurred by nostalgia, but even the original arcade version from the 80s was more exciting and felt a lot more mysterious and immersive. This new version is a very generic representation of the concept----------------------------------------------------------------------------------This review is not going to be a fair one. I'm not sure the game deserves any more fairness than it offered me, though.As you can see, I've barely even played the game. From what little I have seen, the gameplay appears to be fine, although certainly not very complex.The feature that bothers me to no end, is the direly misdesigned multiplayer interface, or more specifically the lack of reasonable options for hosting or searching an online game. When starting a game and you want to join a running multiplayer session, you're given exactly one option: Quick join. The game then searches for a random session and drops you right in the middle of the action. If the host didn't expect you, chances are you'll be kicked, as soon as he/she finds an opportunity that won't get him/her killed.Apparently, someone who starts a game alone automatically hosts it as a multiplayer session. Thus there is an abundance of running games where the host doesn't expect other people to join. So, if you click ""Quick join"" be prepared to be kicked out - a lot.I do not comprehend why someone would design a multiplayer interface of such a rotten quality, but I very much believe that such a person shouldn't earn a single dime from it, regardless of how many other games also use this braindead multiplayer system.I have always known Gauntlet as a cooperative game...accordingly I won't even attempt to rate the single player experience."
