76561198052771946,Not Recommended,258970,18168926,"Posted: 24 September, 2015",all,hexinous,"If you took some of the worst aspects of a Diablo game (rogue-like levels which are composed of all-too-few room types), coupled it with level mechanics which constantly lock you into tiny rooms with overwhelming numbers of monsters, took away the player's ability to manuever or use any real level of tactics, added a rather useless RPG store mechanism which encourages you to die until you and buy enough to stop dying as often, totally ignored any concept of class balance or fair play, constantly spawned invulnerable enemies or one-hit-kill traps against the player, and then slapped a Gauntlet skin and audio track on the mess...  That's this game.It's not a challenge...  It's just keep dying until you can buy enough so you don't.And you won't really know enough about this game to decide whether you like it until you've played too much to get a refund.  It takes hours to figure out that the class balance is completely out of whack.  It takes hours to get upgrades.  It takes hours to figure out that all you really have to do is keep dying...The Gauntlet of old was, at its best, a game of tactics and planning.  You were playing alone or with friends against hordes of enemies, setting up choke points, solving puzzles, sweeping a floor in a careful, methodical method, and pressing on.  It was a game about tactics, planning, and puzzle solving as much as action.  This isn't that game.  This game...  Just run for the gold, hope you can blast enough enemies to keep some of it.  Repeat.  Buy upgrades.  Repeat.So, if you like mindless action and lots of dying, go for it.  But I can't even really call it Gauntlet.  It lacks Gauntlet's spirit."
